Foreign governments in the West including the US have regarded Mubarak as an important ally and [[Foreign relations of Egypt#Israeli-Palestinian conflict|supporter]] in the [[Israeli-Palestinian conflict|Israeli-Palestinian]] peace negotiations.<ref name="Hosni Mubarak" /> After wars with [[Israel]] in 1948, '56, '67 and '73, Egypt signed a [[EgyptâIsrael Peace Treaty|peace treaty]] in 1979, provoking controversy in the [[Arab world]]. As provisioned in the 1978 [[Camp David Accords]], which led to the peace treaty, both Israel and Egypt receive billions of dollars in aid annually from the United States, with Egypt receiving over US$1.3 billion of military aid each year in addition to economic and development assistance.<ref>{{cite web| title = Background Note: Egypt| publisher=[[United States Department of State]]| date=10 November 2010| url = http://www.state.gov/r/pa/ei/bgn/5309.htm| accessdate=28 January 2011}}</ref> According to Juan Cole, many Egyptian youth feel ignored by Mubarak on the grounds that he is not looking out for their best interests and that he rather serves the interests of the West.<ref name="cole">{{cite news|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2011/01/30/opinion/main20030008.shtml|title=Why Egypt's Class Conflict Is Boiling Over â Juan Cole: How Decades of Economic Stumbles Set the Stage for Egypt's Current Political Turmoil|author=Cole, Juan (essay)|date=30 January 2011|work=[[CBS News]]|accessdate=4 February 2011}}</ref> The cooperation of the Egyptian regime in enforcing the [[blockade of the Gaza Strip]] was also deeply unpopular amongst the general Egyptian public.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2008/jan/25/egypt.israelandthepalestinians1 |title=Mubarak under pressure | World news | guardian.co.uk |work=Guardian |location=UK |accessdate=6 February 2011 |date=25 January 2008}}</ref>

===Online activism and the role of social media===
  +
{{Ref improve section|date=July 2011}}
  +
[[We are all Khaled Said|We Are All Khaled Saeed]] is a Facebook group which formed in the aftermath of Saeed's beating and death. The group attracted hundreds of thousands of members worldwide and played a prominent role in spreading and bringing attention to the growing discontent. As the protests began, Google executive [[Wael Ghonim]] revealed that he was the person behind the account.<ref>{{cite news|title = Who is Wael Ghonim?|date=8 February 2011|publisher=Canadian Broadcasting Corporation|url = http://www.cbc.ca/world/story/2011/02/08/f-wael-ghonim.html|work=CBC News|accessdate=17 February 2011}}</ref> Later after the revolution, in an TV interview in the presence of member of the ruling military council, it was revealed that AbdulRahman Mansour, a young underground activist and media expert shared the account with Wael Ghonim.<ref>{{cite news|title = ØªÙØ±ÙØ± Ø®Ø§Øµ- ÙÙ Ø¯Ø§Ø®Ù Ø§ÙØ«ÙØ±Ø© Ø§ÙÙØµØ±ÙØ©|url = http://ara.reuters.com/article/topNews/idARACAE73C0QW20110413?sp=true|date=13 April 2011|agency=Reuters |format = transcript|accessdate=6 February 2011}}</ref> Another potent viral online contribution was made by [[Asmaa Mahfouz]], a female activist who posted a video in which she challenged people to publicly protest.<ref>{{cite news|title = Women play vital role in Egypt's uprising|url = http://www.npr.org/2011/02/04/133497422/Women-Play-Vital-Role-In-Egypts-Uprising|date=4 February 2011|work=National Public Radio|format = transcript|accessdate=6 February 2011}}</ref> Previously, Facebook had suspended the group because some of its administrators were using pseudonyms, a violation of the company's 'Terms of Service.'<ref>{{cite news|title = Can Egypt's Internet Movement Be Exported?|date=18 February 2011|publisher=[[The Nation]]|url = http://www.thenation.com/print/article/158717/can-egypts-internet-movement-be-exported|work=The Nation|accessdate=23 February 2011}}</ref>

It is readily believed that a handful of people through Facebook, Twitter, and blogging sparked this uprising. One of which is [[Wael Ghonim]] . Many believe Ghonim was the first contributor to spark the Egypt revolution when he created a Facebook page dedicated to Khaled Saeed entitled [[We are all Khaled Said|We Are All Khaled Saeed]] . Saeed, an Egyptian business man was beaten to death by police in June 2010. It is believed that this was in retaliation to a video he posted showing Egyptian police sharing the spoils of a drug bust. The Facebook page blew up to over 400,000 followers, creating an online arena where protestors and those discontent with the government could gather, vent, and organise. The page called for protests on 25 January, Known as the day of wrath. Hundreds of thousands of protestors flooded the streets to show their discontent with the murder and the corruption within their country. Ghonim was jailed the 28th and released 12 days later. Ghonim has also gained quite a large following through his Twitter account where he has been creating a narrative of the events happening day to day in Egypt. Ghonim is the Middle East and North African marketing manager at Google. He is currently on leave.
  +   +
Another major contributor is Egyptian activist and member of the 6 April movement
  +   +
Though these two are credited with being the first social media faces of this revolution, since the 25th people have posted videos, tweeted, and wrote Facebook comments to keep the world abreast of the turmoil in Egypt. Including videos posted of a badly beaten Khaled Said, disproving the first claims by the police that he had choked to death. Ali documents the various ways in which social media was used by Egyptian activists, some of the most prominent Egyptian celebrities, and as well by major political figures abroad to invigorate the protests.<ref name="Ali185-189">{{cite journal |first=Amir |last=Ali |url=http://harvardhrj.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/09/185-220.pdf |title=The Power of Social Media in Developing Nations: New Tools for Closing the Global Digital Divide and Beyond |journal=Harvard Human Rights Journal |volume=24 |issue=1 |pages=185â189, 208â210 }}</ref>
  +   +
The role of social media in the Egyptian uprising has since been widely written and debated about, including in the first edition of the [[Dubai Debates]] on the question "Mark Zuckerberg â the new hero of the Arab people?"
  +
<ref>[http://www.dubaidebates.com/debates/view/1/mark-zuckerberg-the-new-hero-of-the-arab-people]</ref> Many have argued, based in part on the Egyptian revolution, that social media may be an effective tool in developing nations more generally.<ref name="Ali205-208">{{cite journal |first=Amir |last=Ali |url=http://harvardhrj.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/09/185-220.pdf |title=The Power of Social Media in Developing Nations: New Tools for Closing the Global Digital Divide and Beyond |journal=Harvard Human Rights Journal |volume=24 |issue=1 |pages=205â208 }}</ref>

== After-Revolution Freedom of Establishing Political Parties ==
  +   +
Freedom was given to establish political parties only by "notifying" concerned authorities resulted in establishing several political parties named after or in relation to the 25 of January revolution. [[List of political parties in Egypt]]
